name: Greg Flasck
text:
My family has been visiting Sailboat Bay for nearly two decades and have found it to be the perfect year-round spot. It's tucked away from all the seasonal craziness, but is still close to lots of great places to eat & shop. Yes, it's not on the beach, but trust me - that's a huge plus.

It's a great development for boat owners, each unit has a slip that puts you right on the ICW or Bon Secuor bay. Fishing, with or without a boat, is great - residents regularly catch redfish, drum, I've even caught juvenile blacktip shark on the bay.

Sunsets on the bay are amazing - just amazing.  Whether you're looking to live in or visit Gulf Shores, Sailboat Bay is really a special place, don't overlook this Gulf Shores gem.

name: will will
text: All these horrible and selfish reviews from people who didn't get what they wanted, when they wanted, and how they wanted it. I came to the Christian Mission over 3 yrs ago and was admitted into their New Life Center program. I have been affiliated with them ever since. I entered this place from jail, a drug-addicted sinner of the worst kind. I was treated with compassion, love, and respect without earning (or deserving) any of it. I have seen such good works done here. Meals to the home-bound, three meals a day to local "walk-ups", financial assistance and food to those IN NEED, etc. Is the Christian Mission perfect? No. Because it's run by flawed human beings...who are doing their best to follow God's will that we love and serve one another. These people get paid a pittance (those that do get paid), they do this for something greater than themselves. Does the Mission help EVERYBODY who comes in wanting something? No, because EVERYBODY wants something for nothing...so they have to determine (to the best of their ability) how to help. This place has helped so many, but we tend to only hear from the few it doesn't... Those OUTSPOKEN few who probably aren't telling the whole story of WHY they couldn't be helped. But God bless them all.

name: Leeanne Gunther
text:
This may be a lengthy review.. but this is worth the read if you are considering Frontier for internet service.

On September 14th, I had an appointment to have high speed internet installed. However, I received a phone call a couple days before hand (they left a voicemail) that I would not be receiving internet services.

I called at 11:44am and was placed on hold for quite some time and could not stay on the phone for any longer as my lunch break was over.
I called again at 4:14pm. This call lasted 11 minutes. I was told that I could not get high speed but that I could get 12mb.

September 15th
I called Frontier again and I was told I could only get 6mb, then the statement was retracted, and I was told that I could not get any internet service at my location. I questioned this as I had been previously told that I could get 6mb, then I was told once again that I actually could get 6mb. So then I scheduled an appointment for 10/6/2020 to have the internet installed.

October 6th
Frontier was scheduled to come between 1pm-5pm. I had to work, so I had a friend come over to my house on their day off so someone could be there. Frontier came at 9:30am and left a note on the door that they needed to bury a drop box. I called frontier at 11:31am wondering why someone had arrived so early. I was on the phone until 11:47am during my lunch at work trying to get this figured out, but did not receive any answers. I was not very happy, as I assumed I would be receiving internet services this day. I would think that Frontier would know if I had a drop box at my house already? Frontier left me a voicemail that someone would be coming to run the lines for my internet on October 20th, and I would get internet installed on October 26th.

October 26th
I received a text reminder on October 25th to remind me of my upcoming appointment with Frontier. I also received another text message reminder on October 26th that Frontier would be coming to my house between 1pm-5pm. Once again, I had someone at my house as I usually work during these hours. Frontier never came... I called Frontier at 4:57pm wondering what was going on. Once again, I didn't really receive an answer. I was told that the department that I needed to talk to was already gone for the day and that they would give me a call the next day.

October 27th
I called Frontier again.. and explained that I have never had so many problems with a company before. I explained that I have been trying to get internet from them for almost 2 months now.. and I have had nothing but problems. They told me that a subcontractor needs to come out and run the lines before they can install internet... they also explained that they should be contacting me soon.. which I obviously didn't believe at this point. I told them I was very dissatisfied and that I would be going with a different internet company at this point.

October 30th
I went with a different company and have internet and am currently using it with no problems :)

text: I have had frontier, by default, internet service for about 4 years now. since I signed up with them, it's been nothing but problems. I have had so many service calls for lack of speed(supposed to be "up to" 6mbps but had maybe 1) and frequent internet drops or disconnects. First, I want to say, the technicians hands are tied as far what they can do. they are doing the best they can to put band aids on these old lines and keep them running. But still to this day, I have quite a few internet disconnects a day. I have just given up on them ever fixing the problem and should mention that this happens every year sometimes more than once were my internet will just stop working and they fix it And then it works fine for a few weeks then it goes back to frequent disconnects and so on. the technicians have measured as many as 400 disconnects in a 24 hr period. If they would just upgrade these lines and may run some fiber optic to some of the main hubs then these problems would stop. I wish I could say I'm the only one with these problem.s but my neighbors all say the same thing. I was told these lines were originally only run to be used for phone. But my parents live next door and they always  have issues with both internet and phone. they have lots of really loud staic in the lines and sometime buzzing so loud you can't hear anything and often times the phone just doesn't work. so even if these lines in our area were supposed to be used primarily for landline phones, obviously they aren't sufficient for that either. so why not replace them with new lines and have satisfied customers instead of reviews and complaints like this? because they don't care about those of us who are getting terrible service. they have no competition here to worry about so they know they can ignore us and continue to collect our money. the moment another company moves in, a lot of us in this area will be switching. name: Linda Bomes
text: This is really amazing of a lot of these post....some saying, how they have been checking them out and finding none are Cherokee,  whining that they are only" State Recognize not Federal"...another one stating " DNA testing for enrollment"..Let me set some things straight..If you have been checking their lineage out and finding they are not Cherokee, show me the evidence..I am a Novice Genealogist working towards my board, would love to see your evidence IF you indeed did any of the extensive work involved.... DNA testing  for Ancestry DOES NOT TELL YOU WHAT TRIBE  and IS NOT a basis for enrollment into any tribe, but the Eastern Band accepts the DNA testing for parentage purposes only.....But I will be glad to show you mine which shows what generations my Native American side comes in, there are numerous Federal Recognized Tribes AND there are numerous State Recognized Tribes, yes you read that right...State Recognized Tribes can also petition to become Federal, and that has happened. Here's another FACT, The Indian Arts and Crafts Act under The Department of The Interior states this INDIAN TRIBE: #1) Means Any federally recognized Indian tribe, band, nation, Alaska Native village or organized group or community or ....#2) Any Indian group that has been formally recognized as an Indian tribe by a STATE LEGISLATURE, a STATE COMMISSION, or another similar organization vested with STATE LEGISLATIVE TRIBAL  RECOGNITION AUTHORITY....and this means that State Recognized tribes can sell their arts and crafts as Native American made, this is FEDERAL LAW...A lot of you base what an Native should look like on the Hollywood stereo types, I knew one one with the eastern Cherokee who is red hair, green eyed and fair skin and is 3/4 blood..and..it is not about what you look like , it is about your lineage, how the blood line comes down to you, a Cherokee is a Cherokee..period..So all of you who complain and blah , blah this and blah blah that, show me your evidence..it took me just over 25 years to complete my genealogy to show my Cherokee ancestry and lineage and I had to send in a copy to the Echota Band and they checked it out, you see you have to PROVE on your part to a State Recognized tribe just like you have to PROVE YOUR GENEALOGY to the Federal tribes. The same goes as for a CDIB card, you have to PROVE DIRECT DESCENDANCY from a Cherokee ancestor..Shoe me YOUR evidence

resp.text:
Your passion for your Tribe is admirable, as is your commitment to demonstration of genealogy!
We would like to address one statement you made; although "Federally Recognized" status may be attainable, we as a "State Recognized" Tribe have no intention of pursuing Federal Recognition.

name: Tooni One Feather
text:
This tribe is a state recognized tribe through the Alabama Indian Affairs Commission. And members must prove their native ancestry to receive a roll number. Many of their native ancestors are on no lists or rolls because they chose not to - the level of trust wasn't high. Some married whites, and some simply disappeared into the mountains and woods. One can only imagine what they might do in this situation - get in line, or run?
I have been a member of this tribe since 1986. And at that time, my family and I had to prove our native ancestry. Which was no easy task back then. It was traced to my 2nd great grandmother who married a white man and was listed as mulatto until the census finally added the choice for "Indian" under the Color column.
Her choice of survival doesn't strip her of her heritage. Other records are there.

name: Brian “VC” voncannon
text: Fine people. They are proud like anyone else. If everyone is worried about people lying and playing Indian, then you better read all the articles about what happened at the OK main tribe, as well as the now REQUIRED DNA TESTING for membership in the Eastern Band. Not long ago, the council (I know a few) had the tribe audited. Guess what? Found non-Tsalagis on the rolls, getting per capita checks and everything. PLUS, they found via DNA, that some WEREN'T NATIVE AT ALL. So, remember, when you point a finger at someone, there are three fingers pointing back at you. Yes, I am enrolled. Had to prove my stuff too. Only AKC registered animals and Natives have to PROVE lineage. Actually, roll numbers, CDIBs are an insult. This "fake indian" has relatives that were enrolled and many not. I spend time with the EBCI and another tribe my father descended from. But this is a review about the Echota. Again, fine people. If anyone is lying about their heritage, then it WILL catch up to that person some day. But please don't let one rotten potato destroy the whole bag. Would you like me to introduce you to some "REAL CHEROKEES" who live in Murphy or Bryson City, NC who DON'T QUALIFY FOR MEMBERSHIP IN THE EASTERN BAND? Many are much more than the required 1/16. Its about casinos, money, etc. today, not the one drop rule of Cherokee citizenship that used to be. When I published a Cherokee book, dedicated to my Grandpa Lambert (in the EBCI library, across from the high school), people came out of the woodwork with the "here's a fake medicine man trying to scam people out of money". I don't even know what they were talking about, but getting a little sick. Who cares who has a roll number? BUT, who cares about money? Please note, folks who need help and cant get it because of the shysters, break my heart. I watched an elderly Cherokee woman beg the EBCI tribal council at a meeting, for help with her power bill in tears. She was rejected. I don't know why, but like I said, I DONT LIKE PEOPLE WHO PRETEND TO BE INDIAN FOR PROFIT MYSELF, but please be careful with folks like Echota whose ancestors may not be on the Dawes, Miller, Baker, Hester, Rez, rolls, etc. for whatever reason. And by the way, at one time, Cherokee family stories within the tribe WAS LAW. White men documented the Cherokee people until the Phoenix was published after Sequoya invented the syllabary. And even "CHEROKEE" is not a native word. It's of French origins. Tsalagi is the correct term, as is Ani-yunwiya, and Ani-Kituah (the principal people, and the people of God). Ask the elders about Bryson City, NC (Kituah) and it's significance.  God bless and for Pete's sake, can we just agree that we are ALL simply human beings made by the Creator?

text: We rented the building for a church event and had a great time here.  The staff that let us in was very friendly and on time.  We had plenty of tables and chairs to do what we needed to do. The kitchen was perfect for our needs. The best part was the park across the street that all the kids were able to play in for the day.  They had a great time and got to spend some quality time outdoors.  We were very happy with the service!
